char.label: Autapomorphies of A. nicoi such as the dorsal spinelet associated with a rigid dorsal-fin spine; the horizontal bony lamina developed only on last three centra and compound ural centrum, and the absence of procurrent caudal-fin rays (Fig. 1; Friel, 1994, 1995)
Metapterygoid absent (Fig. 5, also in Aspredinini; vs. present)
Two proximal pectoral-fin radials (Fig. 7, also in Xyliphius sofiae; vs. three)
Lateral vertebral process associated with last vertebrae
Distinguished from all other aspredinid species by its reduced number of fin rays: four pectoral-fin rays (vs. five or more)
Two dorsal- fin rays (vs. three or more, except Amaralia hypsiura)
Four to five anal-fin rays (vs. six or more, except Bunocephalus verrucosus)
Extension of the contact between parapophysis of complex vertebrae and fifth vertebra reduced (Fig. 2; vs. contact large, same extension of lateral blade of parapophysis of complex vertebrae, Fig. 1)
Hemal spines contacting anal-fin pterygiophores simple (vs. bifid); modally two ribs (Fig. 2; vs. modally five, Fig. 1)
Middle nuchal plate not contacting the posterior nuchal plate laterally (Fig. 2; vs. middle nuchal plate contacting laterally posterior nuchal plate, Fig. 1)
Ossified infraorbital canal tubules present (vs. absent)
Keratinized tubercles over caudal peduncle scattered (Figs. 3–4; vs. keratinized tubercles forming aligned rows)
Pectoral fin mostly dark pigmented (Figs. 3–4; vs. pectoral fin mostly hyaline
Branchial aperture positioned ventrally (Figs. 3–4; vs. branchial aperture positioned ventrolaterally)
Nine caudal-fin rays (vs. 10, except Hoplomyzontinae, Amaralia, Platystacus, Bunocephalus chamaizelus, and Bunocephalus minerim)

It is distinguished from its single congener, A. nicoi, by features mentioned in the amended genus diagnosis and additionally by possessing lateral wings on urohyal (vs. urohyal reduced, wings absent)
Four epibranchials, typical uncinate process on third epibranchial absent
Distal portion of anterior margin of pectoral-fin spine
First and second pharyngobranchials absent or unossified
Third and fourth ossified, suspending expanded tooth plate with elongate acicular teeth
Gill rakers absent in first two ceratobranchials, feeble on remaining ones
Preopercle-mandibular canal absent anteriorly with single tubular ossification anterior to its entering in preopercle
Typical small tubular ossification located at lateral line canal between pterotic and posttemporal-supracleithrum absent
Single thin and elongated procurrent caudal-fin ray in both lobes, additional small and sliver-like on ventral lobe
